                <p><em>In the frozen heart of the Ural Mountains, where the wind howls like a banshee and the snow never stops falling, lies a mystery that has haunted Russia for over six decades.</em></p>

                <p>On January 23, 1959, nine experienced hikers led by <strong>Igor Dyatlov</strong> set out on what should have been a routine winter trek through the Ural Mountains. They were all students and graduates of the Ural Polytechnic Institute, skilled mountaineers who had completed similar expeditions before. Their destination was <strong>Mount Otorten</strong>, a peak that translates to "Don't Go There" in the local Mansi language.</p>

                <p>But they never reached their destination. Instead, they became the center of one of the most baffling mysteries in modern history—a case that has spawned countless theories, official investigations, and even a Hollywood movie.</p>

